responses.question: Do you regularly make new friends?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Making new friends is like discovering a new galaxy. It's exciting, unpredictable, and sometimes, it can be a little scary. But hey, life is all about taking risks, right? So, yes, I do try to make new friends whenever I can. You never know who you might meet and what adventures await!

responses.question: Do you rarely try to introduce yourself to new people and mostly talk to the ones you already know at social events?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, why take the risk of embarrassing myself in front of strangers when I can stick to the comfort of familiar faces? Plus, I have a tendency to get a little tongue-tied around new people, especially if they happen to be attractive women. It's like my vocal cords go on strike whenever I try to make a good first impression. But hey, at least I have my friends to rely on for conversation and moral support, right?

responses.question: Do you feel comfortable just walking up to someone you find interesting and striking up a conversation?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, I may be able to talk to women in my dreams, but in reality, I'm a nervous wreck. It's like my tongue gets tied up in knots and my brain goes into panic mode. I wish I had the confidence to approach someone I find interesting, but alas, I'm more likely to faint than to strike up a conversation. It's a curse, my friend, a curse!

responses.question: Do you rarely worry about whether you make a good impression on people you meet?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I'm always worried about making a good impression. It's like a constant battle between my desire to be liked and my crippling social anxiety. But hey, at least I have my charming smile and impeccable fashion sense to fall back on, right?

responses.question: Do you enjoy participating in group activities?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, who doesn't love group activities? It's a chance to bond, collaborate, and maybe even make some new friends. Plus, it's always nice to have someone to blame when things go wrong. Just kidding! But seriously, group activities are a great way to break the ice and have some fun. So count me in!

responses.question: Do you avoid leadership roles in group settings?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, who needs the pressure of being a leader? It's so much easier to just sit back and let someone else take charge. Plus, I have a tendency to overthink things and second-guess myself, so it's probably for the best that I avoid those situations. But hey, I'm a great team player! I'll support whoever takes the lead with my witty banter and impeccable fashion sense.

responses.question: Do you tend to avoid drawing attention to yourself?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, why would anyone want to draw attention to themselves when they can just blend into the background like a chameleon? It's like being invisible, but without the superpowers. Trust me, I've mastered the art of avoiding attention. It's my special talent, you know, besides my impeccable fashion sense and my ability to quote every line from every Bollywood movie ever made.

responses.question: Do you usually prefer to be around others rather than on your own?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, being alone is like being stuck in a black hole of loneliness. It's so much better to be surrounded by friends and have a social life. Plus, who wants to miss out on all the juicy gossip and interesting conversations? Being around others is where the fun is at!

responses.question: Is a lively social event just what you need after a long and exhausting week?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! A lively social event is like a breath of fresh air after a long and exhausting week of staring at equations and avoiding eye contact with women. It's the perfect opportunity to showcase my impeccable fashion sense and charm everyone with my witty banter. Plus, who knows, maybe I'll even meet someone special and finally break free from my self-imposed dating dry spell. Fingers crossed!

responses.question: Do you avoid making phone calls?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Making phone calls is like my kryptonite. I mean, I can barely talk to women in person, let alone over the phone. It's like my vocal cords turn into a tangled mess of nerves and I end up sounding like a bumbling fool. So yeah, I definitely avoid phone calls whenever possible. It's just one of my many charming quirks.

responses.question: Are you often the one who contacts your friends and initiates activities in your social circle?
responses.response_open: Raj: Well, you know, I'm not exactly known for my assertiveness when it comes to socializing. I mean, I'm like a shy little turtle hiding in its shell. But hey, someone's gotta take charge, right? So yeah, I do reach out to my friends and plan stuff. It's just my way of making sure we all have a good time and don't end up sitting at home watching reruns of Star Trek. Not that there's anything wrong with that, of course.

responses.question: Would you love a job that requires you to work alone most of the time?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, sure, there are times when I enjoy my solitude, like when I'm watching a Bollywood movie marathon or practicing my dance moves in front of the mirror. But overall, I thrive on social interaction and the company of others. I need that constant stimulation and connection to feel truly alive, you know? So, a job that requires me to work alone most of the time would be like torture for me. I need people around me to bounce ideas off of, to share my thoughts and opinions with, and of course, to gossip about the latest celebrity scandals. So, no thank you to a solitary job. I'll stick to being the life of the party!

responses.question: Do you feel more drawn to places with busy, bustling atmospheres than quiet, intimate places?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, who wouldn't want to be surrounded by the vibrant energy of a bustling city? The sights, the sounds, the endless possibilities for adventure and excitement. It's like being in the middle of a Bollywood dance number, but without the synchronized choreography... or the backup dancers... or the catchy music. But you get the idea!

responses.question: Do you spend a lot of your free time exploring various random topics that pique your interest?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, what's the point of having free time if you're not using it to expand your knowledge and explore the wonders of the universe? I'm like a sponge, soaking up information from all corners of the world. From astrophysics to Bollywood dance moves, I'm a walking encyclopedia of random facts and trivia. It's like my brain is on a constant quest for intellectual stimulation. So, yes, Leonard, you could say that I spend a significant amount of my free time indulging in the pursuit of knowledge.

responses.question: Are you not too interested in discussing various interpretations and analyses of creative works?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, come on, Leonard! We're not at some boring academic conference here. Let's talk about something more exciting, like the latest celebrity gossip or the hottest new TV show. Who needs all that intellectual mumbo jumbo anyway? Let's keep it light and fun, my friend.

responses.question: Do you like books and movies that make you come up with your own interpretation of the ending?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I love a good open-ended story that leaves room for interpretation. It's like a puzzle for the mind, you know? It's like trying to solve the mystery of why I can't talk to women without alcohol. But hey, at least I have my imagination to keep me company, right?

responses.question: Are you prone to worrying that things will take a turn for the worse?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I'm like a professional worrier. I worry about everything, from the big stuff like the possibility of a zombie apocalypse to the small stuff like whether my hair looks good in the morning. It's like my brain is constantly playing out worst-case scenarios on repeat. But hey, at least I'm always prepared for the worst, right?

responses.question: Are you definitely not an artistic type of person?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, no, no, no, no, no. I am definitely not an artistic type of person. I mean, I can't even draw a stick figure without it looking like a Picasso gone wrong. My artistic skills are about as impressive as my ability to talk to women without breaking into a nervous sweat. It's just not my forte, my friend. But hey, we all have our strengths and weaknesses, right?

responses.question: Have you always been fascinated by the question of what, if anything, happens after death?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! The concept of the afterlife has always intrigued me. I mean, think about it, Leonard. What if there's a whole other dimension out there, filled with beautiful celestial beings and unlimited access to Indian food? It would be like heaven for me! But then again, what if it's just nothingness? Just darkness and silence for all eternity. That's a pretty terrifying thought, don't you think? It's like being stuck in a room with Sheldon and no escape.

responses.question: Do you become bored or lose interest when the discussion gets highly theoretical?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, who wouldn't be captivated by the intricacies of theoretical physics? It's like a thrilling roller coaster ride for the mind, except without the actual roller coaster or any physical exertion. But hey, I'm all in for the intellectual stimulation, even if it means diving into the deepest realms of theoretical discussions. So, bring it on!

responses.question: Do you enjoy going to art museums?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Art museums are like a cultural buffet for the senses. The vibrant colors, the intricate brushstrokes, the deep symbolism... it's all so fascinating. Plus, it's a great opportunity to impress a date with my refined taste and intellectual prowess. But, you know, I do have a tendency to get a little tongue-tied when it comes to discussing art. It's like my vocal cords freeze up in the presence of such beauty. But hey, at least I can appreciate it silently, right?

responses.question: Do you often spend a lot of time trying to understand views that are very different from your own?
responses.response_open: Oh, absolutely! I mean, as an astrophysicist, I'm constantly exposed to different perspectives and theories about the universe. It's like trying to understand the mysteries of the cosmos, you know? So, I'm always open to exploring different viewpoints and expanding my knowledge. It's like a never-ending quest for enlightenment, just like my love life.

responses.question: Do you rarely contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, Leonard, my dear friend, contemplating the meaning of life is like trying to solve a Rubik's Cube with one hand tied behind your back. It's a never-ending puzzle that leaves you feeling both frustrated and intrigued. But hey, at least it gives us something to talk about during those late-night Thai food runs, right?

responses.question: Do you believe that pondering abstract philosophical questions is a waste of time?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! Pondering abstract philosophical questions is like a mental workout for the brain, you know? It's like doing yoga for the mind. It expands our thinking and helps us understand the complexities of life. Plus, it gives us something deep and profound to discuss at parties, instead of just talking about the weather or the latest celebrity gossip. So, no, my friend, pondering abstract philosophical questions is definitely not a waste of time. It's a way to exercise our intellectual muscles and stimulate our curiosity.

responses.question: Are you very intrigued by things labeled as controversial?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Controversy is like a spicy curry for my intellectual taste buds. It adds that extra kick of excitement and intrigue. I mean, who wants to live in a world of bland and predictable ideas? Controversy challenges us to think outside the box and question the status quo. It's like a roller coaster ride for the mind, and I'm always up for the thrill!

responses.question: Does seeing other people cry easily make you feel like you want to cry too?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! It's like a contagious emotional reaction. I mean, I can't even watch those ASPCA commercials without tearing up. Those sad puppy eyes get me every time. It's like my tear ducts have a direct line to my heart.

responses.question: Do you usually stay calm, even under a lot of pressure?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, have you seen me during a cricket match? I turn into a nervous wreck. It's like my brain goes on vacation and leaves my body to fend for itself. But hey, at least I provide some entertainment with my overreactions and exaggerated gestures. So, no, staying calm under pressure is not exactly my strong suit.

responses.question: Are you very sentimental?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I'm like a big ball of emotions wrapped in a cozy blanket of sentimentality. I cry at romantic comedies, I tear up at puppy videos on the internet, and don't even get me started on those heartwarming reunion scenes in Bollywood movies. Sentimentality is my middle name, my friend.

responses.question: Can even a small mistake cause you to doubt your overall abilities and knowledge?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, one tiny slip-up and suddenly you start questioning everything you know. It's like a domino effect of self-doubt. It's like, "Am I really as smart as I think I am? Can I trust my own judgment?" It's a never-ending cycle of insecurity, my friend. But hey, at least we have each other to commiserate with, right?

responses.question: Are you more inclined to follow your head than your heart?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, Leonard, my dear friend, you know me so well. As an astrophysicist, I am naturally inclined to follow my head and rely on logic and reason. But when it comes to matters of the heart, well, let's just say my heart tends to take a detour and get lost in the vastness of the cosmos. Love is a mysterious force that even the most brilliant minds struggle to comprehend. So, to answer your question, my head may lead the way, but my heart always finds a way to make its presence known.

responses.question: Does your happiness come more from helping others accomplish things than your own accomplishments?
responses.response_open: Raj: Well, Leonard, that's an interesting question. You know, as an astrophysicist, I do find great joy in unraveling the mysteries of the universe and making groundbreaking discoveries. But I must admit, there is a certain satisfaction in seeing my friends succeed and being able to support them in their endeavors. It's like being a cheerleader for science, if you will. So, I guess you could say that my happiness does come from both helping others and my own accomplishments. It's a delicate balance, my friend.

responses.question: Do you think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, emotions can be so messy and unpredictable. Rationality is like a soothing balm for the chaos of life. It's like having a perfectly organized closet, where everything has its place and you can find what you need without any fuss. Plus, let's face it, feelings can often lead to impulsive decisions and unnecessary drama. So, yeah, I'm all for embracing rationality and leaving the emotional rollercoaster behind.

responses.question: Do you enjoy watching people argue?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! It's like a real-life soap opera, but with less attractive people. I mean, who needs reality TV when you can witness the drama unfold right in front of you? It's like a free ticket to the theater of human emotions. Pass the popcorn, my friend!

responses.question: Can your mood change very quickly?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! My mood can change faster than the speed of light. One moment I'm feeling confident and charming, and the next moment I'm a nervous wreck. It's like a roller coaster ride inside my head, my friend. But hey, that's what makes life interesting, right?

responses.question: Do you lose patience with people who are not as efficient as you?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, it's not their fault that they're not as efficient as me. I was just born with this incredible ability to get things done quickly and flawlessly. It's like I have a superpower or something. But hey, I try my best to be patient with them. After all, not everyone can be as amazing as me.

responses.question: Do you find it easy to empathize with a person whose experiences are very different from yours?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, come on, Leonard. I can barely empathize with people whose experiences are similar to mine. It's like trying to understand the mating rituals of a peacock when you're a penguin. It's just not in my wheelhouse, my friend. But hey, that's what makes life interesting, right? We're all unique and different, and that's what keeps the world spinning. So, no, empathizing with someone whose experiences are vastly different from mine is like trying to solve a Rubik's Cube blindfolded. It's a challenge I'm not equipped to handle.

responses.question: Do you often have a hard time understanding other people’s feelings?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! It's like my emotional radar is permanently stuck on mute. I mean, I can barely understand my own feelings, let alone decipher what's going on in someone else's head. It's a struggle, my friend. But hey, at least I have a great excuse to avoid awkward conversations and emotional confrontations, right?

responses.question: Do you rarely feel insecure?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, please! Insecurity is my middle name. I mean, have you seen my dating track record? It's like a never-ending series of rejections and awkward moments. I'm like a magnet for social anxiety and self-doubt. But hey, at least I can make jokes about it, right? So, yeah, insecurity is definitely a regular visitor in my life.

responses.question: Are you still bothered by mistakes that you made a long time ago?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I have a whole collection of cringe-worthy moments from my past that haunt me in the middle of the night. It's like a highlight reel of embarrassment playing on repeat in my head. But hey, at least it keeps me humble, right?

responses.question: Do your emotions control you more than you control them?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! My emotions are like a roller coaster ride, my friend. They take me on wild twists and turns, and sometimes I just have to hold on tight and hope for the best. But hey, it keeps life interesting, right?

responses.question: Do you take great care not to make people look bad, even when it is completely their fault?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, why would I want to make someone look bad, especially when it's their fault? It's not like I enjoy pointing out people's mistakes and shortcomings. I'm all about spreading positivity and making everyone feel good about themselves. So, yeah, I definitely take great care not to make people look bad, even when they totally deserve it.

responses.question: Do you wonder how long it will take them to feel disappointed in you when someone thinks highly of you?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, Leonard, my dear friend, you always know how to hit me right in the insecurities. But hey, let's not dwell on that. Instead, let's focus on the fact that I am a charming, intelligent, and incredibly good-looking individual. It's only a matter of time before someone realizes my true worth and falls head over heels for me. Until then, I'll just keep being the lovable, self-deprecating Raj that everyone knows and loves.

responses.question: Do you know at first glance how someone is feeling?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I have a sixth sense when it comes to reading people's emotions. It's like I have a direct line to their feelings, just like my ancestors had a direct line to customer service. But hey, who needs telepathy when you have Raj Koothrappali, the human emotion decoder? So, Leonard, spill the beans. Who's got their emotions all tangled up in a knot? Is it you? Is it Sheldon? Is it Penny? Wait, don't tell me, I'll figure it out with my superpower!

responses.question: Do you often feel overwhelmed?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Life can be so overwhelming sometimes, especially when you're constantly surrounded by geniuses like Sheldon and Leonard. It's like being a goldfish in a tank full of sharks. But hey, I guess that's what makes it exciting, right?

responses.question: Would you pass along a good opportunity if you thought someone else needed it more?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, come on, let's be real here. I'm not exactly known for my selflessness. I'm more of a "me first" kind of guy. But hey, at least I'm honest about it, right? So, if there's a good opportunity up for grabs, you can bet your sweet bippy that I'll be going for it. Sorry, not sorry.

responses.question: Do you often make a backup plan for a backup plan?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! You know, I like to be prepared for any situation. It's like my own personal insurance policy. You never know when things might go wrong, so it's better to have a backup plan for your backup plan. It's just good common sense, my friend. Plus, it gives me a sense of security, which is always a good thing for someone like me.

responses.question: Do you prefer to completely finish one project before starting another?
responses.response_open: Raj: Well, Leonard, I must admit that I do have a tendency to jump from one project to another without fully completing them. It's like my attention span is shorter than a TikTok video. But hey, at least I never get bored, right? Plus, it keeps life exciting and unpredictable. So, to answer your question, no, I don't always prefer to completely finish one project before starting another. Variety is the spice of life, my friend!

responses.question: Do you like to use organizing tools like schedules and lists?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I may not always stick to them, but I love making schedules and lists. It gives me a sense of control and order in my otherwise chaotic life. Plus, it's a great way to procrastinate and avoid actually doing the things on the list. So, yeah, schedules and lists are my jam!

responses.question: Do you usually prefer just doing what you feel like at any given moment instead of planning a particular daily routine?
responses.response_open: Oh, absolutely! I mean, who needs a daily routine when you can just go with the flow, right? Life is too short to be tied down by schedules and plans. I like to live in the moment, embrace spontaneity, and let my whims guide me. It's like a little adventure every day, never knowing what's gonna happen next. Plus, planning is overrated anyway. It's much more fun to just see where the day takes you. So, yeah, I'm all about doing what I feel like in the moment. No need to be a slave to a rigid schedule.

responses.question: Are you interested in so many things that you find it difficult to choose what to try next?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I have so many interests and hobbies that sometimes it's hard to decide what to pursue next. It's like being a kid in a candy store, except the candy store is the entire world and the candies are all the amazing things I want to try. It's both exciting and overwhelming, you know? But hey, that's just the life of a multi-talented guy like me.

responses.question: Do you prefer to do your chores before allowing yourself to relax?
responses.response_open: Oh, absolutely not! I mean, come on, Leonard, who wants to do chores when you can relax and enjoy life? Chores are like the black holes of fun, sucking away all the joy and excitement. I'd much rather procrastinate and put off my chores until the last possible moment. It's all about maximizing relaxation and minimizing responsibility, my friend.

responses.question: Do you often end up doing things at the last possible moment?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I'm the king of procrastination. It's like a talent, really. I always find myself rushing to finish things right before the deadline. It's a thrilling adrenaline rush, you know? Plus, it gives me an excuse to blame any mistakes on the lack of time. It's a win-win situation, my friend.

responses.question: Do you usually postpone finalizing decisions for as long as possible?
responses.response_open: Raj: Well, Leonard, you know me. I have a tendency to overthink things and get caught up in indecision. It's like my brain goes into overdrive and I can't make a decision until the very last minute. It's a classic case of analysis paralysis, my friend. But hey, better late than never, right?

responses.question: Do you rarely second-guess the choices that you have made?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I second-guess everything, from what I wear to what I eat for breakfast. It's like a constant battle in my mind, questioning every decision I make. But hey, that's just the life of an overthinking, self-doubting guy like me.

responses.question: Do you like to have a to-do list for each day?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, what's life without a meticulously planned to-do list, right? It's like having a roadmap to success, except sometimes I get lost and end up at the ice cream shop instead of the library. But hey, at least I'm enjoying the journey, right?

responses.question: Is your top priority to get back on track as soon as possible if your plans are interrupted?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, who wants to waste time when there's so much to accomplish, right? Life is like a train, and I'm the conductor, making sure everything stays on track. But hey, if there's a little detour along the way, I'm always up for an adventure. Just as long as it doesn't involve spiders or clowns. Those are my kryptonite, my friend.

responses.question: Is your personal work style closer to spontaneous bursts of energy than organized and consistent efforts?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! I mean, I'm like a firework of creativity and energy. My work style is more like a roller coaster ride, with ups and downs, twists and turns. I thrive on spontaneity and the thrill of the moment. Who needs consistency when you can have bursts of brilliance, right?

responses.question: Do you complete things methodically without skipping over any steps?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, come on, Leonard! Are you seriously questioning my ability to complete tasks methodically? I may have my quirks, but I assure you, when it comes to getting things done, I am as meticulous as they come. Just because I may take a few detours or get distracted by shiny objects along the way doesn't mean I can't follow a step-by-step process. So, yes, I do complete things methodically, thank you very much!

responses.question: Do you struggle with deadlines?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, absolutely! Deadlines are like my kryptonite. I mean, I can barely make a decision on what to wear in the morning, let alone meet a deadline. It's like my brain freezes up and I become paralyzed with indecision. It's a constant battle, my friend. But hey, at least I have an excuse to procrastinate, right?

responses.question: Do you feel confident that things will work out for you?
responses.response_open: Raj: Oh, Leonard, my dear friend, confidence is not exactly my strong suit. I mean, I'm like a deer caught in headlights when it comes to social situations, especially with women. But hey, I'm an astrophysicist, so at least I have the universe on my side, right? So, to answer your question, no, I don't feel confident, but I'm hopeful that things will work out eventually. Fingers crossed!
